'''Adam Marshall''' {{Post-nominals|country=||list=[[Society of Jesus|SJ]]}} (November 18, 1785&nbsp;– September 20, 1825) was an American [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] priest and [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]]. He briefly served as president of [[Gonzaga College High School|Washington Seminary]], and later became the first Catholic chaplain in the [[United States Navy]], albeit unofficially.

== Biography ==
Adam Marshall was born on November 18, 1785<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jRfdAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=adam+marshall+conewago&source=bl&ots=HH4hC8umIJ&sig=oqFcz6YOtHuk3yKXbXRRP_A-xEM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjWp43OuL7dAhXsmOAKHTR-DZ8Q6AEwCXoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=adam%20marshall%20conewago&f=false|title=Stephen Larigaudelle Dubuisson, S.J. (1786–1864) and the Reform of the American Jesuits|last=Buckley|first=Cornelius Michael|publisher=[[University Press of America]]|year=2013|isbn=9780761862321|location=Lanham, Maryland|pages=129|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916021137/https://books.google.com/books?id=jRfdAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=adam+marshall+conewago&source=bl&ots=HH4hC8umIJ&sig=oqFcz6YOtHuk3yKXbXRRP_A-xEM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjWp43OuL7dAhXsmOAKHTR-DZ8Q6AEwCXoECAEQAQ%23v=onepage&q=adam%20marshall%20conewago&f=false#v=snippet&q=adam%20marshall%20conewago&f=false|archive-date=September 16, 2018|dead-url=no}}</ref> in [[Conewago, Pennsylvania]], to Francis Marshall and Ann Margaret Staub; he had two sisters named Margaret and Catherine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thomasgenweb.com/staub.pdf|title=Descendants of John Adam Staub, of Conewago & McSherrystown, Adams County, Pennsylvania|last=Thomas|first=Jeffrey L.|date=February 22, 2008|website=Thomas Family Genealogy Website|page=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827211358/http://thomasgenweb.com/staub.pdf|archive-date=August 27, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> As a [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] priest, he first served in 1818 at St. Patrick's Church in [[York, Pennsylvania]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stpatrickyork.org/listing-of-priests-who-have-served-saint-patricks|title=Listing of Priests who have Served Saint Patrick's|last=|first=|date=|website=Saint Patrick Catholic Church|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916015259/https://stpatrickyork.org/listing-of-priests-who-have-served-saint-patricks|archive-date=September 16, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref> and later worked in [[New York (state)|New York]], the southern counties of [[Maryland]], and at [[Georgetown University|Georgetown College]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name="historyII" />

Marshall became the most powerful figure in the Jesuit mission in Maryland, eventually becoming the [[Procurator (canon law)|Procurator]] of the Corporation of Roman Catholic Clergymen of Maryland during the [[suppression of the Society of Jesus]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BWQb_GWZcWcC&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=adam+marshall+sj&source=bl&ots=MUKrvmnQlx&sig=fd77qekCUgJ_AwFxO6C-MRKifKU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwix_Im3tL7dAhURhuAKHVAoDH84ChDoATAOegQIAxAB#v=onepage&q=adam%20marshall%20sj&f=false|title=Shaping American Catholicism: Maryland and New York, 1805–1915|last=Curran|first=Robert Emmett|publisher=[[Catholic University of America Press]]|year=2012|isbn=9780813219677|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=62|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916020635/https://books.google.com/books?id=BWQb_GWZcWcC&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=adam+marshall+sj&source=bl&ots=MUKrvmnQlx&sig=fd77qekCUgJ_AwFxO6C-MRKifKU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwix_Im3tL7dAhURhuAKHVAoDH84ChDoATAOegQIAxAB%23v=onepage&q=adam%20marshall%20sj&f=false#v=snippet&q=adam%20marshall%20sj&f=false|archive-date=September 16, 2018|dead-url=no}}</ref>

In 1822, he was stationed at Washington Seminary (which later became [[Gonzaga College High School]]) and was placed in charge of the worldly affairs of the Jesuit mission in Maryland. In the beginning of 1824, Marshall was appointed the second president of Washington Seminary, succeeding [[Anthony Kohlmann]]. During his presidency, the students of the Seminary partook in the first civic procession in Washington by joining in the commemoration of the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]] on the [[Independence Day (United States)|Fourth of July]] of 1824. While president, Marshall also gave a speech at Georgetown College during a reception for the [[Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette|Marquis de Lafayette]], with his students in attendance.<ref name="historyII">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mZoaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27&dq=adam+marshall+sj&source=bl&ots=GJ7XfrUDUI&sig=fqyVCl2Hpg9yObpquPQFgwGDgsA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi_j6Wfnr7dAhXJY98KHayDAnoQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=adam%20marshall%20sj&f=false|title=Gonzaga College, an Historical Sketch: From Its Foundation in 1821, to the Solemn Celebration of Its First Centenary in 1921|last=Hill|first=Owen Aloysius|publisher=Gonzaga College High School|year=1922|isbn=|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=29–32|chapter=Chapter II: Fr. Adam Marhsall, S.J. (1824–1825)|oclc=1266588|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916005550/https://books.google.com/books?id=mZoaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27&dq=adam+marshall+sj&source=bl&ots=GJ7XfrUDUI&sig=fqyVCl2Hpg9yObpquPQFgwGDgsA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi_j6Wfnr7dAhXJY98KHayDAnoQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=adam%20marshall%20sj&f=false|archive-date=September 16, 2018|dead-url=no}}</ref>

Marshall became ill with [[tuberculosis]]<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XkuMqnM-89wC&pg=PA10&lpg=PA10&dq=adam+marshall+sj&source=bl&ots=XWqf00cHgX&sig=x0HSznKZab66ZtbyjSdESkt4I0k&hl=en&sa=X&sqi=2&ved=2ahUKEwjs8NCUsL7dAhXOGuwKHRHuATEQ6AEwBnoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=adam%20marshall%20sj&f=false|title=Blackrobe in Blue: The Naval Chaplaincy of John P. Foley, S.J. 1942|last=O'Brien|first=Steve|publisher=[[iUniverse]]|year=2002|isbn=9780595226948|location=|pages=10|chapter=Chapter 1: "The Sword of the Spirit"|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916014602/https://books.google.com/books?id=XkuMqnM-89wC&pg=PA10&lpg=PA10&dq=adam+marshall+sj&source=bl&ots=XWqf00cHgX&sig=x0HSznKZab66ZtbyjSdESkt4I0k&hl=en&sa=X&sqi=2&ved=2ahUKEwjs8NCUsL7dAhXOGuwKHRHuATEQ6AEwBnoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=adam%20marshall%20sj&f=false|archive-date=September 16, 2018|dead-url=no}}</ref> that affected his lungs.<ref name="woodstockXCI">{{Cite journal|last=Giblin|first=Gerard F.|date=April 1, 1962|title=American Jesuits as Chaplains in the Armed Forces: 1775 to 1917|url=https://jesuitonlinelibrary.bc.edu/?a=d&d=wlet19620401-01.2.3|dead-url=no|journal=Woodstock Letters|volume=XCI|issue=2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916013133/https://jesuitonlinelibrary.bc.edu/?a=d&d=wlet19620401-01.2.3|archive-date=September 16, 2018|via=Jesuit Online Library}}</ref> His physicians advised that he take a reprieve from duties at the school and recommended he undertake a sea voyage. Through the intervention of Commodore [[John Rodgers (1772–1838)|John Rogers]], whose two sons were students at Gonzaga, Marshall obtained a position in the [[United States Navy]].<ref name="historyII" /> He was succeeded as president of the school by [[William Matthews (priest)|William Matthews]].<ref name="historyIII">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mZoaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Gonzaga College, an Historical Sketch: From Its Foundation in 1821, to the Solemn Celebration of Its First Centenary in 1921|last=Hill|first=Owen Aloysius|publisher=Gonzaga College High School|year=1922|isbn=|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=29–32|chapter=Chapter III: Rev. Jeremiah Keiley, S.J. (1826–1827)|oclc=1266588|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916012049/https://books.google.com/books?id=mZoaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=September 16, 2018|dead-url=no}}</ref>

Marshall was commissioned an officer in 1824 and was assigned to the [[USS North Carolina (1820)|USS ''North Carolina'']], a [[ship of the line]].<ref name="chaplain">{{Cite news|url=https://www.catholiceducation.org/en/faith-and-character/faith-and-character/a-chaplain-s-chaplain.html|title=A Chaplain's Chaplain|last=Duffy|first=Peter|date=2008|work=Catholic Education Resource Center|access-date=September 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916002921/https://www.catholiceducation.org/en/faith-and-character/faith-and-character/a-chaplain-s-chaplain.html|archive-date=September 16, 2018|dead-url=no}}</ref> His official position was schoolmaster to the midshipmen, but he unofficially<ref name="woodstockXCI" /> doubled as [[Military chaplain|chaplain]] to the Catholic sailors, making him the first Catholic chaplain in the United States Navy.<ref name=":0" /><ref name="woodstockLXX">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1 October 1941|title=First Catholic Chaplains in U.S. Army and Navy|url=https://jesuitonlinelibrary.bc.edu/?a=d&d=wlet19411001-01.1.131&e=-------en-20--21--txt-txIN-------|dead-url=no|journal=Woodstock Letters|volume=LXX|issue=3|pages=466–467|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916002819/https://jesuitonlinelibrary.bc.edu/?a=d&d=wlet19411001-01.1.131&e=-------en-20--21--txt-txIN-------|archive-date=September 16, 2018|access-date=September 15, 2018|via=Jesuit Online Library}}</ref> The religious services on board were conducted by an [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]] minister whose sermons Marshall noted that he admired, and Marshall was not permitted to say [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Mass]]; rather, his duty was to counsel and hear [[Sacrament of Penance|confession]].<ref name="woodstockXCI" />

The ''North Carolina'' left port in [[Norfolk, Virginia]], on December 1, 1824,<ref name="historyII" /> for a cruise of the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. In the final entry of Marshall's diary, the lieutenant of the watch notes that while underway, at 2:30&nbsp;a.m. on September 20, 1825, during the voyage from [[Naples]] to [[Gibraltar]],<ref name="historyII" /> the priest died of his disease.<ref name="woodstockXCI" /> He was [[Burial at sea|buried at sea]] at 10&nbsp;a.m. with all hands on deck.<ref name="woodstockLXX" /> On October 22, Commodore Rogers communicated the news to the [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Secretary of the Navy]].<ref name="historyII" />

